Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

sql_query = """
select p.permit, Applicant, count(distinct locationid) number_of_locations
from mobile_food_permits p
inner join mobile_food_schedule s on s.permit = p.permit
where Status = 'APPROVED'
group by p.permit
order by "number_of_locations" desc
"""

In this question, I connect tables mobile_food_permits and mobile_food_schedule with the common column permit and calculate the count of locations for each permit and select permit number, Applicant (the name of mobile food vendor) and count of locations from the connected table and sort the location counts from high to low.

As a result, from the final table, we can see that mobile food vendor "Park's Catering" sells at the most locations and the number of locations is 23. "D&T Catering" and "F&C Catering" also sell at many locations, of which the numbers are 17 and 13 respectively.

Exercise 1.2. Ask and use the database to analyze 5 questions about San Francisco. For each question, write at least 150 words and support your answer with plots. Make a map for at least 2 of the 5 questions.

You should try to come up with some questions on your own, but these are examples of reasonable questions:

  • Which parts of the city are the most and least expensive?
  • Which parts of the city are the most dangerous (and at what times)?
  • Are noise complaints and mobile food vendors related?
  • What are the best times and places to find food trucks?
  • Is there a relationship between housing prices and any of the other tables?

Please make sure to clearly state each of your questions in your submission.

In this question, I use table "crime" and select incident number, day of week and district. Then I count the number of distinct incident numbers by district and day of week. I make a bar plot for crime number with time and place and I find that the most dangerous time and part of the city is Friday in Southern district of San Francisco, with a number of crime incidents 24869. I also select only incident number and day of week and calculate the number of distinct incident numbers by day of week. I make a bar plot for crime number with time and and I find that the most dangerous time in San Francisco is Friday, with a number of incidents as high as 123861. As a result, people will have high risk to enroll in a crime incident in Friday and especially in Southern district of San Francisco and they should avoid going out at that time and in that district.

In this question, I use tables 'noise' and 'mobile_food_locations', and I use the longitude and latitude information in these two tables. To see the relationship between noise complaints and mobile food vendors, I want to draw all the noise complaints points with blue points and all approved mobile food vendors with red points and see their distribution on the shapefile, which is plotted by module called 'shapefile'. From the plot above, I find that in the northeast part of the city, especially in Financial District and South of Market District according to Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods, noise complaint points distribute around mobile food vendors, however, in other district, noise complaint points seem to distribute far away with mobile food vendors. As a result, noise complaint has relationship with mobile food vendors in Financial District and South of Market District, while in other districts of the city, noise complaint has no relationship with mobile food vendors.

In this question, to detect what are the best times and places to find food trucks, I use tables mobile_food_locations, mobile_food_permits and mobile_food_schedule, I select permit, locationid, day of week, latitude and longitude where facility type of mobile vendors is truck. I first group the records by day of week and calculate the count of distinct permits. I find that Friday is the best time to find approved food trucks since there are 119 food trucks in distinct locations (here I use select distinct locations instead of distinct permits since there are food trucks that sell in different places at the same time). Then I map the distribution of food trucks on Friday. I use the packages 'folium' and 'geopandas' to complete the map. I also use the shapefile of neighborhood in San Francisco to plot the boundary for this analysis and also for different districts.

From the first plot, we can see that food trucks are concentrated in northeast part of the city as well as southeast part of the city. But since there are so many points, we can not see very clearly which districts have most food trucks.

In the second plot, I use 'Marker Cluster' to let near points get together into one big point and the number on this point means how many food trucks are concentrated in this place. The second plot is more clear than the first one. According to the map for different district in the shapefile, we can see that Financial District, South Of Market District, Mission Bay District, Dogpatch District, Produce Market District, Bayview District have most concentrated food trucks and they are all working places, markets and sightseeing places, which are supposed to have so many approved food trucks according to common sense.

import zipcode
latitude = []
longitude = []
for i in range(0,len(mean_house_price)):
    Lon = zipcode.isequal(str(mean_house_price['RegionName'][i])).lon
    Lat = zipcode.isequal(str(mean_house_price['RegionName'][i])).lat
    latitude.append(Lat)
    longitude.append(Lon)
mean_house_price['Lat'] = latitude
mean_house_price['Lon'] = longitude

In this question, I want to explore the relationship between housing price and the distribution of schools, that is, whether housing price in a region is higher than others due to more schools in this region. I use tables schools and zillow in database and calulate the mean of 'MedianSoldPricePerSqft' in table zillow grouped by region. I also convert zip code into latitude and longitude with package 'zipcode'. I make a map of housing price and distribution of schools, in which blue mark represents the center of each region and it has a popup of mean housing price when clicking on it and circle represents the number of schools near this circle. From the plot, we can see that many schools concentrate in the northeast region and in regions with 43, 26, 35 schools, the housing prices are above 600 per square feet, which is a much higher price compared with other regions. There are also many schools in the center region, such as there is a place with 24 schools and the housing price is 650 per square feet there. As a result, we can conclude that a region with many schools would have a high housing price. However, in South Beach District, although it does not have so many schools, it still has a housing price as high as 798 per square feet, and I guess maybe the reason is that it is near the coast line and it is also an important financial district.

In this question, I want to explore the relationship between public parking places and the location of civic plaza or square since I find that it is difficult to find public parking place whenever go shopping in civic plaza in San Francisco. I use tables parking and parks in database, for parking, I just select records with Owner 'SFMTA' since I think it represents public parking places and for parks, I just select records with Type 'Civic Plaza or Square'. From the result above, blue mark represents civic plaza and with popup of its name, cicles represent the number of public parking places near it, we can see that most civic plazas have few public parking places around them expect for 'Union Square', with as many as 10 public parking places around it since it is the most popular place for shopping. As a result, I think maybe more public parking places should be built up around other civic plazas or squares for much more convenient for residents.
